Hola! It’s @simplyfloritza again! Today I’m coming with our last recipe in the series, soup! Sofrito is an excellent soup base and an easy way to add flavor to your broth.  I love a good soup and tend to make this often because it is also a great way to get your veggies! 
.
.
.
Ingredients: 
Two frozen sofrito pods 
1/2 lb. seasoned beef meatballs 
Olive oil 
1.5 cups chicken stock 
1.5 cups water 
Choice of veggies (carrots, celery, onions, garlic, potatoes)
Choice of vegetable noodles (I use one spiraled zucchini) 
Salt and pepper to taste 
.
.
Directions:
1. In a pot, sauté onions in olive oil. 
2. Add beef meatballs and cook until slightly browned
3. Add garlic and sofrito pod and Mix well, follow by adding remaining veggies and stir. 
4. Add chicken stock and water and allow to simmer 
5. Follow with a second sofrito pod and salt and pepper to taste. 
6. Add zucchini noodles and allow to simmer for 5 min. 
7. Serve hot. 
.
.
.
Remember to find the sofrito recipe, go to @simplyfloritza and click the highlight titled “sofrito”. You can also find that and so many other recipes by checking out my YouTube channel Simplyfloritza! 
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

👋 Hey friends! We’re Abe and Isaac (@abelopez), husbands and creators. We run a company called Lightward, because that’s what we know: to move in the direction that feels like light. We were here last February, too—thanks for having us back! 😄

OUR THEME THIS WEEK: Where you are is REAL and we can WORK with that, to good-feeling, positive ends. Begin where you are, and believe you can make something good with what you have. 💪

** Hey I’m Abe! I’ve been sharing my health story at #abeminus100. Growing up with mostly processed/fast food and zero veggies, I never thought about what food could really do for me. In my late 20s, after a few health scares, I realized I just wanted to feel GOOD in my body. And then I found W30! It’s been a huge part of this turnaround, giving me space to fully reset and rebuild my relationship to food, losing the sugar/fries addictions, learning to love my body more and more, and giving me a new appreciation for food as something that makes my life better every day.

Today, I’m down 65lbs, and #abeminus100 has become so much more than weight loss for me. It’s about loving my body in all the ways that I can, and celebrating him every day. Every day in this beautiful body of mine is a gift.

** I’m Isaac! My whole deal is the journey to *understand*, and to build with the things I’m learning to understand. I grew up on a potato farm in the woods of northern Wisconsin, as the eldest of five. School took me to Chicago, where I spent a bunch of years beginning to seriously unfold. And I met Abe exactly seven years ago, as I write this on April 4. 🥰 Happy anniversary, darling.

My health story is a constant conversation with my body. I have strong trust for what my gut tells me, for what my heart can hear, and for what my mind can discern. All of this shows up in how I run Lightward, and it shows up in how I cook. 😄 W30 was when I started to understand food, from the salt-fat-acid-heat side of things to the ingredients themselves. (Have you ever just stared at a vegetable for five minutes? TRY IT.) I love living and exploring, and this takeover with Abe is a part of that. 🙃

** Love y’all! Pumped for this week—thanks for being here.

1) Not one Whole30 is the same. Your W30 will look different than mine and that’s OK. I just wanted to let you know you have a place here, whatever knowledge you wanna take away from the Whole30 program there will always be room for you at the table here.
2) Show yourself grace and enjoy the journey. It’s not overnight, it might not be after 30 days but I hope you now have the tools to cultivate a food freedom fit for YOU.

✨UKOY (Filipino Fritters)✨
Coach Alexis @asideofalexis with my last coaching tip:
Let’s talk shallow fry, nut butters, nuts and dried fruit. All Whole30 compatible but if these types of  foods or snacks trigger your “food with no breaks” or your sugar dragon, proceed with caution and some self-awareness. Check in with yourself, have that internal dialogue. This kind of self reflection is vital when it comes to cultivating a food freedom specific to you and your individual needs.
•
Now we’ve come full circle to the first recipe I shared. Remember that Crispy Sweet Potato Nest from last week? Its origin actually comes from my Tita’s (aunt) Ukoy recipe. Ukoy (pronounced ooh-coy) is a Filipino root vegetable fritter with tiny shrimp. Any root vegetable works but my Tita keeps hers simple with just shredded carrots.

UKOY (ooh-coy)
@asideofalexis
Serves 6-7
•
Ingredients:
2 bags of shredded carrots
1 cup frozen baby/tiny shrimp, roughly chopped (excess water removed)
3-4 green onion stalks, thinly sliced 
Enough arrowroot powder to coat ingredients evenly. 
•
Instructions:

REMOVE frozen bay shrimp from the freezer and set aside for about 10 min.
RINSE under cold water and remove excess water with a paper towel or cheese cloth. CHOP shrimp, small dice.
COMBINE shredded carrots, shrimp, chopped scallions.
ADD 2-3 tbsp. arrowroot powder or until everything is evenly coated. Toss together.
PREHEAT large skillet with 1/4”-1/2” of avocado oil. Not too much, just a shallow fry.
ADD a small handful of your shrimp-carrot mixture and gently place in the hot oil.
*You can use tongs instead of your hands if hot oil make you nervous.
FRY on med.-high heat. Adjust burner if they brown too quickly. Fry until edges start to crisp and fritter is more formed.
FLIP and fry another few minutes.
*You can turn the Ukoy occasionally to crisp evenly.
DRAIN on paper towel or cooling rack and immediately sprinkle with sea salt.
•
Dipping Sauce aka sukang sawsawan:
1/3 cup W30 compatible vinegar
1 garlic clove, pressed
1 sliced serrano or 2-3 labuyo peppers
Cracked pepper and pinch of sea salt

✨CHICKEN ADOBO✨ 
Whole30 coach Alexis @sideofalexis here on my last day with you but first, growing up Sundays were “family days” and Sunday supper was mandatory no matter what everybody’s social calendars were. So I thought we could do the same today! I’ve got two Filipino recipes for you that I’m sure will be a hit on your table too.

Chicken/Pork Adobo is a staple in any Filipino household. In the video tutorial the marinade ratios stated are for smaller batches of Adobo but the ratio is still the same for larger batches like the recipe below. 2:1 coconut aminos to vinegar.
Could you make this in the IP or slow cooker? Yes you absolutely can. But will it be just as tasty as Lola‘s (grandma)? I’ll let you be the judge but for now let’s keep it old school, stovetop style...
•
CHICKEN ADOBO 
@asideofalexis
Serves 4-6

Ingredients:

3-4 lbs m. bone-in chicken, dark and breast
2 cups coconut aminos
1/2 cup of apple cider vinegar
1/2 cup rice vinegar 
palm full peppercorns
whole head of cracked garlic cloves
4 bay leaves.

Instructions:

PLACE chicken in pot. Add all ingredients.
MARINATE chicken all day or overnight.
REMOVE chicken from the fridge when ready to eat. 
SEAR marinated chicken in a large wok or shallow pot with 2 tbsp. avocado oil.
BROWN each piece of chicken until it has a nice color on them and set aside.
ADD all the chicken and marinade back into wok. The marinade will eventually reduce and cook off.
COVER and braise on medium-low. for  40ish min.
*tip* Do not stir/touch the chicken and marinade for the first 10-15 min. Let the vinegar cook off and the sauce reduce.
TURN chicken over halfway through to cook evenly letting the chicken get nice and tender falling off the bone. 

*You can do this in the slow cooker on high 4 hrs or in the IP 1-2 hrs but the sauce won’t reduce or be as thick as it would stovetop.
•
Crispy Umami Broccolirice
Ingredients:
1 bag of pearled broccoli/broccoli rice
1 tbsp @nomnompaleo’s magic mushroom powder
Enough olive oil to lightly coat evenly.

Instructions:
Toss ingredients together on a sheet pan and roast 425-450° for 20-25 min or until airy, light and crispy. Ovens vary.

✨ZOODLE PRIMAVERA✨
Whole30 Coach Alexis here from @asideofalexis and let’s talk cravings! I conceptualized this dish one day when I had a craving for pasta primavera. Which I know must have been the sugar dragon talking because pasta isn’t even a part of my food freedom. But it happens. Sometimes the sugar dragon kicks in when you least expect it. So I reflected on my craving and instead of fighting it, I embraced it. I daydreamed about what I really wanted from this dish (yes, I daydream about food all day long):
1. Some thing fun to twirl and slurp
2. Yummy savory sausage
3. Fresh vegetables

ZOODLE PRIMAVERA
@asideofalexis
Serves 4-6

Ingredients:
3-4 boxes of frozen zoodles of 6 large zucchini
1 package of compatible sausages, sliced or diced
1 small container of mushroomed, sliced
1 onion
3-4 garlic cloves
1 bunch of bitter greens, coarsely chopped
@thenewprimal Citrus Herb seasoning
Parsley, garnish

Directions:
BROWN sausage in a large skillet with 1 tbsp. olive oil on med.-high heat.
SAUTÉ onion and garlic, about 2-4 min.
ADD mushrooms and citrus herb seasoning, sauté 2-3 min.
ADD Swiss chard or bitter greens and cook down until slightly wilted.
REMOVE from pan and garnish with fresh herbs.
PREP zoodles and serve with sausage primavera on top.
•
ZOODLES

Frozen zoodles:
Add frozen Zoodles directly into the pan with 1 tbsp olive oil and sauté on medium high, defrosting the Zoodles. Drain off excess water. When excess water is removed continue sautéing and season zoodles with citrus herb seasoning.

Fresh Zucchini:
Spiralize zucchini (saving the scraps for a soup or hash). Sauté on high heat cooking off any excess liquid from the zucchini. Season zoodles with citrus herb seasoning.
•
Song: “Call On Me” by Starley, Ryan Riback

Let’s get right to it with this Mexican Chicken Salad! Jess here from @dashof_colorandspice and I love this recipe for various reasons. It is so darn easy, it is full of flavor, and it brings back so many memories! It always takes me back to quinceañeras, bodas (weddings), and family gatherings as I was growing up. I love the fact that it is full of veggies and it is not your typical chicken salad.
Serve it on a bed of lettuce for a delicious salad. This is also perfect for meal prep for the week!

Ingredients
* 2 chicken breasts
* 2 small potatoes
* 2 cups mixed vegetables use canned or frozen
* 1-2 pickled jalapeño, minced
* 1 tbsp jalapeño pickle juice optional
* 1/4 cup mayo 
* s&p to taste
Instructions
* Cook the chicken breast with preferred method. I boil mine with some salted water until cooked through.
* While the chicken is cooking, peel and cut the potatoes into cubes. Place in a pot with salted water over medium high heat. Make sure you check on the potatoes at about 10-15 minutes to see if they are cooked. You want the potatoes soft enough to be pierced with a fork but not too soft that they turn to mush. You don’t want mashed potatoes mixed into the salad.
* While the chicken and potatoes are cooking, defrost the vegetables if they are frozen or drain the canned veggies. Add these along with the mayo, jalapeño, and some s&p to large bowl.
* Once potatoes are done, drain them and run cold water over them to stop the cooking process and cool the potatoes. Drain and add to veggie mix.
* Once chicken is cooked, let it cool for a while, shred it and add to the rest of the ingredients. The chicken can easily be shredded with a hand mixer if you want to save some time.
* Mix everything well and add more s&p if needed. At this time you can also add a little more mayo if you want it creamier. If using jalapeño pickle juice, add now and mix well.
* Place chicken salad in refrigerator for at least an hour. Serve on a bed of lettuce or with cucumber rounds.
Notes
*For a creamier chicken salad add 1 tbsp. mayo at a time and adjust seasoning as needed.

Hola amigos! My name is Jessica and you can find me over at @dashof_colorandspice !
I’m so excited to be here for my 3rd takeover! A little about me:
I am a full-time Oncology nurse living in Kansas City with my husband and two doggos. I am Mexican-American and grew up eating all the delicious Mexican food you can think of. I am bilingual and proud to remake some of the delicious dishes I grew up eating to make them more wholesome and nutritious. If you aren’t new to following me you know I love to use as much flavor and spice as I can. I want to make sure you all know you can go through this Whole30 journey without bland and boring food! I love to introduce new flavors, new ingredients, and new ideas to your food life! I am also a Whole30 Certified Coach!

My Whole30 journey started when I wanted to get better control of my diabetes, high blood pressure, and high cholesterol. I knew food was a huge part of making the necessary changes and starting with Whole30 was a huge step for me. After those 30 days I had amazing improvements in how I felt but most importantly in my numbers. Blood sugars were down, blood pressure was normal, cholesterol much better. Those 30 days helped me realize what foods affected me in what way. It also helped me better read food labels and understand exactly what I’m putting into my body.
I truly believe Whole30 is a great gateway to a better understanding of how good affects our bodies and in what ways.

I am so excited to share some Mexican recipes with you as I do every year. I love recreating those nostalgic dishes I grew up eating them and making them Whole30 compliant!

Thanks for being here and for following along this week. As always, go follow me at @dashof_colorandspice for more recipes and feel free to shoot me a DM and say hello!

Check out my blog https://dashofcolorandspice.com for more recipes!

SALSA CHICKEN STEW 🍲 This recipe from @wholefoodfor7 is one of our most popular posts from 2021. Swipe up from our Story to snag the Whole30 Bundle from @butcher_box so you can keep chicken breasts on hand for any time you want to put this meal together.

From Autumn: “This easy 4-step stew is budget and kid-friendly and includes ingredients you might already have on hand or can find at most grocery stores. It takes only 15 minutes of prep and can be made in your Instant Pot or slow cooker. Don't have a slow cooker or Instant Pot? You can always simmer soups in a large pot on medium-low, covered, on your stove until the veggies are tender and chicken is cooked through!”

INGREDIENTS
2 pounds boneless chicken breasts
2 teaspoons ground cumin
1 1/4 teaspoon salt
1/4 teaspoon pepper
1 teaspoon paprika
1 1/2 cups chicken broth or bone broth
1 cup salsa
3 cloves minced garlic OR 1 teaspoon garlic powder
2 pounds potatoes, cut into 1" chunks (we love orange-fleshed sweet potatoes, but can also use russet potatoes)
1 cup red bell pepper, diced OR 1 cup jarred roasted red pepper
1/3 cup loosely packed fresh cilantro, finely chopped

INSTRUCTIONS
TRIM chicken breasts and cut into strips.
In a small bowl, COMBINE cumin, salt, pepper, paprika, broth, salsa, and garlic.
On the bottom of a 5-6 quart slow cooker or large instant pot, PLACE chopped potatoes. Place chicken and diced red pepper on top of potatoes and pour broth mixture over chicken.
COVER slow cooker with lid and cook on low 8 hours or on high 4 hours. Or seal instant pot and cook on Stew for 25 minutes. Once done, manually release steam released if using instant pot, stir in cilantro and break up chicken as desired (we like large chunks, but shredded works too!).
Serve and enjoy!

Recipe & photo by: @wholefoodfor7 <https://www.instagram.com/wholefoodfor7/>

SMOKY SWEET POTATO CHILI 🍠 We're talking about meal prep this week and this dish from The Whole30 Slow Cooker Cookbook is the perfect meal prep recipe. Throw it in the slow cooker—easy. It makes 5-6 servings—lunch sorted for the week. It's fantastic as leftovers—switch up your toppings for variety. Have you made this fan-favorite chili? What's your favorite way to serve it?

Serves 6
INGREDIENTS
1 1/2 pounds lean ground beef
1 medium red onion, chopped
1 poblano pepper, seeded and diced
2 large sweet potatoes, peeled and cut into [1⁄2]-inch cubes (4 cups)
1 can (10.75 ounces) tomato puree
1 can (15 ounces) crushed tomatoes
2 cups tomato juice
2 tablespoons cider vinegar
1 tablespoon chili powder
1 1/2 teaspoons smoked paprika 
1 teaspoon cumin
1 teaspoon garlic powder
1/2 teaspoon allspice
1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
1 teaspoon smoked salt or regular salt
Finely chopped red onion (optional)

INSTRUCTIONS
IN a large skillet, cook the beef over medium-high heat, stirring with a wooden spoon, until browned, about 10 minutes. Drain off the fat.
TRANSFER the beef to a 4- to 5-quart slow cooker. Add the onion, poblano pepper, sweet potatoes, tomato puree, crushed tomatoes, tomato juice, vinegar, chili powder, smoked paprika, cumin, garlic powder, allspice, cayenne, and salt to the cooker. Stir to combine.
COVER and cook on low for 8 hours or on high for 4 hours.

Recipe from: The Whole30 Slow Cooker by @melissau
Photo by: @sophisticatedcaveman
.

Do you meal prep: 1) In big blocks of time 2) By making leftovers to eat later in the week OR 3) Not at all?

@shannadk here. In Stories last week, 66% of you said you do not meal prep regularly. I’ve gone through phases: sometimes I have a solid meal prep habit, and other times I wing it for every meal.  

Right now as a new mother balancing different dietary preferences in our household, meal prepping is a good way to make sure I always have some food that works for me ready to go. This is a little peek into my early-morning meal prep sessions. As you’re prepping for the #SeptemberWhole30, perhaps my process can help you find what works for you. 

 (And, it’s my first-ever Reel! How did I do?)

Our friends @instantpotofficial and @pyrexhome generously sent me an Instant Pot, SnapWare, and a Pyrex covered glass baking dish. The Instant Pot can cook complex dishes quickly, and when I bake and store in the glass baking dish, I have less things to hand wash. Items like this can streamline your process and make meal prepping a bit more convenient. 

If you are a meal prepare, what’s your best meal prep tip? Share it in the comments to help out other Whole30’ers. 

#mealprep #mealprepideas #instantpot #instantpotrecipes

It's Hatch Chile season! Make a batch of this delicious NEW MEXICO HATCH GREEN CHILE SAUCE from @loubiesandlulu. Have you ever eaten this delicious chile?

This week we are sharing recipes from our Advanced Level Coaches: Whole30 Certified Coaches who have been certified for more than 3 years and have at least 18 CEUs. Pop into our Stories for an incredible roundup of Hatch Chile recipes from  @loubiesandlulu.

Can't get your hands on fresh Hatch Chiles? Freshly roasted, peeled, and chopped #Whole30Approved @ziahatchchileco is a ready-to-use option. In traditional New Mexican cuisine the most common ways to use Hatch Green Chile: 
SAUCE to smother potatoes/hash browns/eggs/veggies
INGREDIENT in dressings, other sauces/aiolis, soups
TOPPING for burgers, scrambled eggs, and more… 

INGREDIENTS
1 tbsp avocado or olive oil
1 lb lean ground beef or turkey. Lean pork diced into bite-sized chunks also works great 
1 cup chopped onion
1–2 cloves minced garlic
1/2 tsp salt
1/2 tsp pepper
1– 16 oz jar @ziahatchchileco (Med or Hot), or about 1 1/2 – 2 cups roasted, peeled, and chopped green chile
1 cup water
1 tbsp arrowroot flour (whisked into 1/4 cup water, right before adding to chile)

INSTRUCTIONS
ADD 1 tbsp oil of your choice to a preheated saucepan 
ADD 1 cup chopped onion and sauté for a few minutes over med heat until translucent, then add 1-2 cloves minced garlic and allow to cook for about 1 minute 
ADD ground beef to the pan. Add 1/2 teaspoon each salt and pepper, breaking meat up into small pieces. Cook on medium heat until fully browned 
ADD 1 jar of @ziahatchchileco and 1 cup water and stir to combine. Bring to a light boil (while you wait whisk 1 tbsp arrowroot flour into 1/4 cup water and set aside)
Once it’s lightly boiling add the whisked arrowroot/water mixture to saucepan and stir well to combine.
TURN heat to low, give it another stir, and allow to simmer at least 20 minutes before serving. 
SMOTHER over your favorite Whole30 breakfast bowl filled with eggs, potatoes, and veggies!

Notes
If you are using fresh or frozen roasted and peeled green chile you will need to add more garlic and salt to taste.

Would you believe it if we told you this salmon went from freezer to air fryer and was ready in 12 minutes? If you're looking for a quick and tasty protein for dinner tonight, stop your scrolling and save this AIR FRYER SALMON from @jacobheathhenriquez.

This week we are sharing recipes from our Advanced Level Coaches: Whole30 Certified Coaches who have been certified for more than 3 years and have at least 18 CEUs. This week is the Whole30 Coach Summit, an exclusive development and mentoring event for our Coaches ... and YOU are invited to the opening night Pep Rally tomorrow! Check out our Story for more information.

METHOD
REMOVE a  6-8 oz frozen salmon filet from its packaging,

SLATHER a tablespoon of ghee on each piece (work quickly because the ghee will harden on the salmon and become unspreadable)

SEASON with your favorite all-purpose spice blend. I used 1 tablespoon of @thenewprimal’s Citrus Herb Seasoning

PLACE in the basket of your air fryer, and cook at 375°F for 11 minutes. 

No preheating, no rotating, nothing! This rendered a crispy exterior but still pink and tender inside. If you like your salmon a bit more done, just two extra minutes will do the trick. This comes in handy when you have frozen seafood on hand and need a meal in a pinch.

An air fryer tip: STOP PUTTING FOIL IN YOUR AIR FRYER. I know it’s “less cleanup,” but it also defeats the purpose of an air fryer. You want heat to circulate all around your food so that you get that nice “fried” exterior. If you’re gonna add foil, you might as well use your oven ✌️

OVEN INSTRUCTIONS
Bake in a covered dish at 400° for about 15 minutes and then uncover and bake for a remaining 8-10 minutes, depending on how done you want it. This helps create steam in the first step which will keep the salmon juicy and tender. 

Image and recipe: @jacobheathhenriquez

This week we are sharing recipes from our Advanced Level Coaches: Whole30 Certified Coaches who have been certified for more than 3 years and have at least 18 CEUs. This week is the Whole30 Coach Summit, an exclusive development and mentoring event for our Coaches ... and YOU are invited to the opening night Pep Rally on Thursday evening. Check out our Story for more information about Whole30 Certified Coaching and the Whole30 Community Pep Rally. 

INGREDIENTS
@nakedbaconco #Whole30Approved Jalapeño Bacon
@butcher_box Chicken Breast
@thenewprimal Classic BBQ Sauce
Whole30 compatible Pickles
Butter Lettuce
Red Onion
Tomatoes

INSTRUCTIONS
COAT chicken breast in BBQ sauce and marinate for 2-3 hours. Overnight is great too! Feel free to fillet chicken breast in half if too thick.

WHEN ready to eat, remove chicken from fridge 30-60 min. before grilling. Grill 3-4 each side on med. high. Adjust cooking time depending on thickness of chicken breast. Remove from heat and rest about 5 min.

ASSEMBLE the sandwich with the rest of your ingredients. Feel free to make it your own with pickled jalapeños or onions, pepperoncinis, in a salad with any lettuce. Arugula is my fav! 

Image and recipe: @asideofalexis

What’s your favorite summer-y salad? 🥗 This week we have 3 salads that pair perfectly with our 3 most popular Made By Whole30 dressings.

Peek at our Stories to learn more about our Made By Whole30 dressings.

Today’s recipe: Grilled Steak and Peach Salad from THE WHOLE30 FRIENDS & FAMILY by @melissau. If you’re short on time, our Creamy Balsamic works perfectly with the savory steak and sweet peach flavors. *Recipe continues in comments.

GRILLED STEAK AND PEACH SALAD

For the Peach Vinaigrette
1 large ripe peach, pitted & coarsely chopped
2 cloves garlic, minced
1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
1/3 cup white wine vinegar
1 tsp coarse salt
1/2 tsp black pepper
1 tbsp Whole30-compatible coarse-grain Dijon mustard
1 tbsp coconut aminos

For the Steak
1/2 cup coconut aminos
1 tsp coarse salt
1 tsp black pepper
1 tsp garlic powder
2 lbs flank steak

For the Salad
4 large ripe peaches, pitted and quartered
2 tbsp avocado oil
3 5-ounce containers spinach and arugula salad blend
2 medium ripe avocados, halved, pitted, peeled, and sliced
4 slices Whole30-compatible bacon, crisp-cooked and crumbled
1 medium red onion, thinly sliced and rings separated
1/2 cup coarsely chopped pecans
 
MAKE the Peach Vinaigrette
In a blender or food processor, combine the peach, garlic, olive oil, vinegar, 1 teaspoon salt, pepper, mustard, & 1 tablespoon coconut aminos. Cover & blend or process until well combined. Store in an airtight container in the refrigerator until ready to serve.

MAKE the Salad
In a small bowl, combine the 1⁄2 cup coconut aminos, 1 teaspoon salt, pepper, & garlic powder. Place the steak in a large resealable plastic bag; add the marinade. Seal and turn to coat the steak. Marinate in the refrigerator, turning occasionally, at least 1 hour or up to overnight.

PREHEAT the grill to medium-high heat. Remove the steak from the marinade & discard the marinade. Arrange the steak on the grill rack. Grill, turning once halfway through, until cooked to desired doneness, 12 to 15 minutes for medium (145°F). 

Photos by: @naderkhouri; Styling by @jjoules
